Chapter 1. Admin Guide

1.1. Overview

   The rust_sst module is a clean Rust implementation of SIP
   Session Timers (RFC 4028) for OpenSIPS. It manages
   Session-Expires and Min-SE header negotiation, dialog lifetime
   management, and re-INVITE/UPDATE refresh handling.

   The module supports two operating modes:

     * Automatic mode - when dialog.so is loaded, the module
       hooks into dialog lifecycle callbacks and handles all SST
       negotiation transparently. No script function calls are
       required beyond create_dialog().

     * Script override mode - when dialog.so is not loaded (or
       for per-call control), the script functions
       rust_sst_check() and rust_sst_update() allow manual
       Session-Expires validation and header construction.

   All timer negotiation logic is extracted into pure, testable
   functions.

1.2. How it works

1.2.1. Automatic mode (dialog integration)

   When dialog.so is loaded, the module registers a DLGCB_CREATED
   callback that intercepts every new INVITE dialog. The sequence
   of operations:

   1. On INVITE (DLGCB_CREATED):
      - Parses Session-Expires, Min-SE, and Supported: timer
        headers from the request.
      - Validates the requested interval against the configured
        default_min_se.
      - If the UAC does not include Session-Expires, the proxy
        inserts one using the configured default_interval.
      - If the UACs Min-SE is below our policy, the proxy
        replaces it.
      - Sets the initial dialog lifetime via $DLG_timeout.
      - Registers per-dialog callbacks for response, in-dialog
        requests, and termination.

   2. On 2XX response (DLGCB_RESPONSE_FWDED):
      - If the UAS includes Session-Expires, the proxy uses it
        (subject to our minimum).
      - If the UAS does not include Session-Expires but the UAC
        supports timer, the proxy inserts Session-Expires and
        Require: timer headers with refresher=uac.
      - Updates the dialog lifetime to match the negotiated
        interval.

   3. On 422 response:
      - Adjusts the internal Min-SE to the value from the 422
        reply to prevent negotiation loops.

   4. On re-INVITE/UPDATE (DLGCB_REQ_WITHIN):
      - Parses Session-Expires from the refresh request/response
        and updates the dialog lifetime accordingly.

   5. On dialog termination (DLGCB_TERMINATED/FAILED/EXPIRED):
      - Cleans up per-dialog SST state and updates statistics.

   Example 1.8. Session timer call flow (automatic mode)
+-------+    +--------+       +-------+
| UAC-1 |    | PROXY  |       | UAC-2 |
+-------+    +--------+       +-------+
    |(1) INVITE     |               |
    |SE: 1800       |               |
    |Supported:timer|               |
    |-------------->|               |
    |  (mod_init registered         |
    |   DLGCB_CREATED)              |
    |               |(2) INVITE     |
    |               |SE: 1800       |
    |               |-------------->|
    |               |               |
    |               |(3) 200 OK     |
    |               |SE: 1800;      |
    |               | refresher=uas |
    |               |<--------------|
    |  (DLGCB_RESPONSE_FWDED:      |
    |   set $DLG_timeout=1800)      |
    |(4) 200 OK     |               |
    |SE: 1800;      |               |
    | refresher=uas |               |
    |<--------------|               |
    |               |               |
    |(5) re-INVITE  |               |
    |SE: 1800       |               |
    |-------------->|               |
    |  (DLGCB_REQ_WITHIN:          |
    |   update $DLG_timeout)        |
    |               |               |
 ...

1.2.2. Script override mode

   When dialog.so is not loaded, or when the operator wants manual
   control, the script functions rust_sst_check() and
   rust_sst_update() are available.

   rust_sst_check() validates the Session-Expires from an incoming
   INVITE against the configured minimum. If the interval is too
   small, it returns -1 and sets $var(sst_min_se) for use in a
   422 reply.

   rust_sst_update() computes the final Session-Expires and Min-SE
   header values for insertion into a 200 OK response.

1.3. Dependencies

1.3.1. OpenSIPS Modules

   The following modules must be loaded before this module:

   For automatic mode:
     * dialog - required for dialog lifecycle callbacks and
       $DLG_timeout.
     * sipmsgops - required for append_hf() and remove_hf()
       used to insert/modify Session-Expires and Min-SE headers.

   For script override mode:
     * sipmsgops - required for append_hf() in the script
       examples.

1.3.2. External Libraries or Applications

   The following libraries or applications must be installed
   before running OpenSIPS with this module loaded:
     * None.

1.4. Exported Parameters

1.4.1. default_interval (integer)

   Default Session-Expires interval in seconds. This is used when
   the UAC does not include a Session-Expires header in the INVITE,
   and as the baseline for negotiation.

   The effective interval is always clamped to be at least as
   large as default_min_se.

   Default value is "1800" (30 minutes).

   Example 1.1. Set default_interval parameter
...
modparam("rust_sst", "default_interval", 3600)
...

1.4.2. default_min_se (integer)

   Default Min-SE value in seconds. This represents the proxy
   minimum acceptable session interval. Per RFC 4028, this value
   must be at least 90 seconds. The module clamps any value below
   90 to 90.

   Default value is "90".

   Example 1.2. Set default_min_se parameter
...
modparam("rust_sst", "default_min_se", 120)
...

1.4.3. default_refresher (string)

   Default refresher role: "uac" or "uas". Determines which
   endpoint is responsible for sending session refresh requests
   (re-INVITEs or UPDATEs) when the UAC does not specify a
   preference.

   Default value is "uas".

   Example 1.3. Set default_refresher parameter
...
modparam("rust_sst", "default_refresher", "uac")
...

1.5. Exported Functions

1.5.1. rust_sst_check(interval, min_se)

   Validate the Session-Expires and Min-SE values from an incoming
   INVITE. The function parses the Session-Expires and Min-SE
   headers from the SIP message and checks them against the
   provided or configured minimums.

   On return, sets $var(sst_interval), $var(sst_min_se), and
   $var(sst_refresher) for use in script logic.

   Parameters:
     * interval (string) - Override for the requested interval.
       Pass "0" to use the value from the Session-Expires header.
     * min_se (string) - Override for the minimum session interval.
       Pass "0" to use the configured default_min_se.

   Return values:
     * 1 - interval is acceptable (at or above the effective
       minimum)
     * -1 - interval is too small. $var(sst_min_se) contains the
       value to use in a 422 reply.

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE.

   Example 1.4. rust_sst_check usage
...
route {
    if (is_method("INVITE") && !has_totag()) {
        if (rust_sst_check("0", "0") == -1) {
            # Session interval too small — send 422
            append_hf("Min-SE: $var(sst_min_se)\r\n");
            sl_send_reply(422, "Session Interval Too Small");
            exit;
        }
        xlog("L_DBG", "SST OK: interval=$var(sst_interval) min_se=$var(sst_min_se) refresher=$var(sst_refresher)\n");
    }
}
...

1.5.2. rust_sst_update(interval, min_se, refresher)

   Compute the Session-Expires and Min-SE header values for a 200
   OK response. The function applies defaults and enforces minimum
   values.

   On return, sets $var(sst_session_expires) to the full
   Session-Expires header value (e.g., "1800;refresher=uas") and
   $var(sst_min_se) to the Min-SE value.

   Parameters:
     * interval (string) - The desired Session-Expires interval.
       Pass "0" to use the configured default_interval.
     * min_se (string) - The desired Min-SE value. Pass "0" to
       use the configured default_min_se.
     * refresher (string) - The refresher role: "uac" or "uas".
       Pass any value; defaults to default_refresher if
       unrecognized.

   Return values:
     * 1 - always succeeds

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.5. rust_sst_update usage
...
onreply_route[sst_reply] {
    if ($rs == "200" && is_method("INVITE")) {
        rust_sst_update("0", "0", "uas");
        append_hf("Session-Expires: $var(sst_session_expires)\r\n");
        append_hf("Min-SE: $var(sst_min_se)\r\n");
    }
}
...

1.6. Exported Pseudo-Variables

   The following pseudo-variables are set by the script functions:

1.6.1. $var(sst_interval)

   The negotiated Session-Expires interval in seconds. Set by
   rust_sst_check().

1.6.2. $var(sst_min_se)

   The effective Min-SE value in seconds. Set by both
   rust_sst_check() and rust_sst_update(). For a 422 reply,
   use this value in the Min-SE header.

1.6.3. $var(sst_refresher)

   The negotiated refresher role ("uac" or "uas"). Set by
   rust_sst_check().

1.6.4. $var(sst_session_expires)

   The complete Session-Expires header value including the
   refresher parameter (e.g., "1800;refresher=uas"). Set by
   rust_sst_update(). Use this directly in append_hf().

1.7. Exported Statistics

1.7.1. sessions_active

   Number of currently active SST-managed dialog sessions
   (automatic mode only).

1.7.2. sessions_expired

   Number of dialog sessions that expired via the session timer
   (automatic mode only).

1.7.3. 422_sent

   Number of 422 "Session Interval Too Small" replies observed
   (automatic mode) or conditions detected (script mode).

1.7.4. headers_inserted

   Number of Session-Expires or Min-SE headers inserted or
   modified by the module (automatic mode only).

   Example 1.6. Complete opensips.cfg example (automatic mode)
...
loadmodule "dialog.so"
loadmodule "sipmsgops.so"
loadmodule "rust_sst.so"

modparam("rust_sst", "default_interval", 1800)
modparam("rust_sst", "default_min_se", 90)
modparam("rust_sst", "default_refresher", "uas")

route {
    if (is_method("INVITE")) {
        create_dialog();
        # SST is handled automatically via dialog callbacks.
        # No additional script logic is needed.
    }
}
...

   Example 1.7. Complete opensips.cfg example (script override mode)
...
loadmodule "sipmsgops.so"
loadmodule "rust_sst.so"

modparam("rust_sst", "default_interval", 1800)
modparam("rust_sst", "default_min_se", 90)
modparam("rust_sst", "default_refresher", "uas")

route {
    if (is_method("INVITE") && !has_totag()) {
        # Validate Session-Expires from the INVITE
        if (rust_sst_check("0", "0") == -1) {
            append_hf("Min-SE: $var(sst_min_se)\r\n");
            sl_send_reply(422, "Session Interval Too Small");
            exit;
        }
    }

    t_on_reply("sst_reply");
}

onreply_route[sst_reply] {
    if ($rs == "200" && is_method("INVITE")) {
        # Compute and insert Session-Expires + Min-SE headers
        rust_sst_update("0", "0", "uas");
        append_hf("Session-Expires: $var(sst_session_expires)\r\n");
        append_hf("Min-SE: $var(sst_min_se)\r\n");
    }
}
...
